FORM.AppraisalAddendumText: -::- -:NEIGHBORHOOD BOUNDARIES:- The immediate neighborhood can be defined as: 1250 S on the north; 1900 W on the east; 4800 S on the south; 4700 W on the west. The market area is the same as the neighborhood and is used for the statistics in the neighborhood section and the 1004MC form. -:COMMENTS ON SALES COMPARISON:- The Comparable Properties bracket the subject in GLA, Sales Price and Adjusted Sales Price. All Comparables, with the exception of Comp 1, are over a mile away and have been used due to the lack of data in the Subject's immediate area. Adjustments are made as follows: An age adjustment has been applied across the board at $1,000 per year of difference. A lot size adjustment has been applied across the board. No comparable properties were available that bracketed on the upper end of lot size. Comps 1, 2 & 3 are similar in GLA and no adjustment is warranted. Comp 4 is a current listing that is smaller in GLA and has been adjusted upwards accordingly. Comps 3 & 4 are superior in condition because the dwellings have not previously been lived in and all materials are new with no deterioration from use. An adjustment to Comp 4 has been applied for median seller concessions in the marketplace. Additional adjustments have been applied on a case by case basis for differences in extra features. The final value is based on Comp 1 because it contains the lowest amount of adjustments and is similar in location and size to the subject. However, the final value has been rounded to $333,000 due to the upward pull of the additional Comparables. -:ADDITIONAL COMMENTS:-

MARKET.SalesConcessionDescription: The WFRMLS MLS indicates there were 32 closed sales during the past 12 months and 25 of those sales contained seller concessions which is 78% of the total transactions in this market area. Prior Months 7-12: 17 Sales; 14 with concessions; 82% of sales for this period. 4-6: 12 Sales; 9 with concessions; 75% of sales for this period. 0-3: 3 Sales; 2 with concessions; 67% of sales for this period. The concessions ranged between 2,126 and 13,571. The median concession amount is $6,100.
MARKET.NeighborhoodMarketabilityFactorsDescript: The WFRMLS MLS indicates there were 32 closed sales during the past 12 months and 3 of those sales were either foreclosures or short sales which is 9% of the total transactions in this market area. Prior Months 7-12: 17 Sales; 0 foreclosures or short sales; 0% of sales for this period. 4-6: 12 Sales; 2 foreclosures or short sales; 17% of sales for this period. 0-3: 3 Sales; 1 foreclosures or short sales; 33% of sales for this period.
MARKET.DataSourceDescription: The WFRMLS MLS was the data source used to complete the Market Conditions Addendum.
MARKET.MarketTrendsReconciliationComment: Effective Date: Wednesday, November 19, 2014 The inventory analysis predominantly indicates a stable market. Although the current months of housing supply are higher than the previous six months, the market is moving in to the slower season and may be responsible for the large indicator. The number of sales for the current six month period is similar to the previous six month period. The median comparable sale price and list price also point to a stable market and improving market. Most other indicators point to a stable or improving market. This information, together with the appraiser's experience and knowledge, indicates a stable market.

LISTING_HISTORY.ListedWithinPreviousYearDescription: The subject was listed through WFRMLS#1263585 on 10/17/2014 for $348,999 and went under contract on 11/15/2014.

PROPERTY_ANALYSIS._Comment: The improvements have been recently constructed and inhabited for a brief amount of time. They feature no deferred maintenance and little or no physical depreciation. All components are new and have virtually no wear from use. The home was constructed from quality materials and has good appeal in the marketplace.
No adverse conditions were noted that would affect the livability, soundness, or structural integrity of the home.
No adverse site conditions or external factors were noted in the area that would adversely affect the subject property's value.
The subject features plantation shutters, ceiling fans, a nest thermostat, granite counter tops, can lighting and a water softner system.

SALES_CONTRACT._ReviewComment: The purchase contract is the standard six page report and contains no addenda. The purchase contract is straight forward with no unusual terms and conditions.

VALUATION_METHODS._AdditionalDescription: The scope of this appraisal included the entire appraisal process, except it was determined that the income approach was not applicable because of a lack of data. The assistance of Eric Larsen is acknowledged in the preparation of this report. He searched public and other records for information about the home. He measured the home and drew the floor plan included herein. He took photos and assisted in the valuation process. Final comparable selection and adjustments were made by Gentry Lawson. The final value conclusion was derived by Gentry Lawson. The cost approach was also reviewed by Gentry Lawson and adjusted as appropriate. Clarification of Intended Use and Intended User: The Intended User of this appraisal report is the Lender/Client and the Federal Housing Administration of the Department of Housing and Urban Development. The Intended Use is to evaluate the property that is the subject of this appraisal for a mortgage finance transaction, subject to the stated Scope of Work, purpose of the appraisal, reporting requirements of this appraisal report form, and Definition of Market Value. No additional Intended Users are identified by the appraiser. At the request of the client, this appraisal report has been prepared in compliance with the Uniform Appraisal Dataset (UAD) from Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac. The UAD requires the appraiser to use standardized responses that include specific formats, definitions, abbreviations, and acronyms. In the normal course of business, the appraiser attempted to obtain an adequate amount of information regarding the subject and comparable properties. Some of the required UAD standardized responses, especially those in which the appraiser has not had the opportunity to verify personally or measure, could mistakenly imply greater precision and reliability in the data than is factually correct or typical in the normal course of business. Consequently, this information should be considered an estimate unless otherwise noted by the appraiser. Selection of a Q4 or Q5 should not be construed as a definitive statement by the appraiser that the subject and/or comparable properties meet the minimum building code of the jurisdiction where the property is located. While an appraiser is expected to have knowledge of the building code, the level of inspection as a result of the Scope of Work for the appraisal assignment is not sufficient in and of itself to determine full compliance with an applicable building code.

COST_ANALYSIS.SiteEstimatedValueComment: Multiple residential lots have sold at a rate between $3.50-$5.00 per square foot. It is typical for larger residential lots to demand compensation on the lower end of the scale per square foot. A figure of $4 has been applied to the Subject's size per square foot and a rounded value of $100,000 was returned. Reference WFRMLS#126675, 1124200, 1124155.
COST_ANALYSIS._Comment: The cost approach is not required for secondary market investors. It is included in this report merely as a cross check of the final value opinion. GLA calculations are taken from actual measurements of the subject improvements. This approach is for valuation purposes and not for insurable value.
